[It is of crucial importance to distinguish infected bats without clinical signs from those that show clear manifestations of the disease. Proper account of this distinction will allow monitoring the evolution of this novel host-parasite interaction (the fungus was introduced into North America less than 10 years ago) as well as to assess the impact on infected bat populations.

The geographical distribution of WNS as of 4 Mar 2015 can be seen at http://whitenosesyndrome.org/resources/map.
A tri-colored bat with evident sings of the disease can be seen here http://dnr.sc.gov/assets/flash_photos/bat2.jpg.
A healthmap of the affected counties can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/awHZ (Saline); http://healthmap.org/r/awH_ (Union); http://healthmap.org/r/awH- (Johnson); http://healthmap.org/r/awH* (Jackson). - Mod.PMB]
